.TH LCH 1 "@DATE@" "leech2 @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lch \- track CSV changes and produce SQL patches
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lch
.RB [ \-C
.IR path ]
.I command
.RI [ args ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lch
is the command-line interface for
.BR leech2 ,
a change data capture tool that tracks CSV table modifications using a git-like
content-addressable block chain. It computes deltas between table snapshots,
stores them as linked blocks, and produces consolidated patches that convert
into SQL statements for replaying changes on a target database.
.PP
A typical workflow is:
.IP 1. 4
Initialize a work directory with
.BR "lch init" .
.IP 2. 4
Edit CSV files and record changes with
.BR "lch block create" .
.IP 3. 4
Generate a patch with
.BR "lch patch create" .
.IP 4. 4
Convert the patch to SQL with
.BR "lch patch sql" .
.IP 5. 4
Mark the patch as applied with
.BR "lch patch applied" ,
or as failed with
.BR "lch patch failed" .
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-C " path"
Run as if started in
.I path
instead of the current directory. This affects where the
.B .leech2
work directory is located.
.TP
.B \-V\fR, \fB\-\-version
Print version information and exit.
.TP
.B \-h\fR, \fB\-\-help
Print help information and exit.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS lch init
Initialize a new
.B .leech2
work directory with an example table configuration and CSV file. Fails if a
configuration already exists.
.SS lch block create
Create a new block from the current CSV state. Reads the configured CSV sources,
computes the new state, diffs it against the previous state, and writes a new
block. History truncation is performed afterwards. Prints the new block's SHA-1
hash to stdout.
.SS lch block show \fR[\fIREF\fR] [\fB\-n \fIN\fR]
Show the full contents of a block.
.TP
.I REF
Block hash or unambiguous hash prefix. Defaults to HEAD.
.TP
.BI \-n " N"
Show the block
.I N
steps back from HEAD. Cannot be combined with
.IR REF .
.SS lch block log
List all blocks from HEAD to genesis, one line per block showing the hash,
timestamp, and table names.
.SS lch patch create \fR[\fIREF\fR] [\fB\-n \fIN\fR]
Create a patch from
.I REF
to HEAD and write it to
.BR .leech2/PATCH .
.TP
.I REF
Block hash or unambiguous hash prefix. Defaults to the REPORTED hash (the last
successfully applied patch), or genesis if nothing has been reported yet.
.TP
.BI \-n " N"
Create a patch covering the last
.I N
blocks. Cannot be combined with
.IR REF .
.SS lch patch show
Show the contents of the
.B .leech2/PATCH
file. Requires a prior
.BR "lch patch create" .
.SS lch patch sql
Convert the
.B .leech2/PATCH
file to SQL statements. Delta payloads generate DELETE, INSERT, and UPDATE
statements. State payloads generate TRUNCATE followed by INSERT statements. All
statements are wrapped in BEGIN / COMMIT. Requires a prior
.BR "lch patch create" .
.SS lch patch inject \fINAME\fR \fIVALUE\fR [\fITYPE\fR]
Add or overwrite an injected field on the
.B .leech2/PATCH
file. The patch is decoded, the field is inserted, and the patch is
re-encoded in place. Repeat the command to inject multiple fields. If a
field with the same
.I NAME
already exists — whether from static configuration or a prior injection —
both its value and type are replaced.
.I TYPE
defaults to
.B TEXT
and accepts the same values as table field types
.RB ( TEXT ,
.BR NUMBER ,
.BR BOOLEAN ).
Requires a prior
.BR "lch patch create" .
.SS lch patch applied
Mark the current patch as applied by saving its head hash to the REPORTED file.
Future patches will start from this point. Requires a prior
.BR "lch patch create" .
.SS lch patch failed
Mark the current patch as failed by removing the REPORTED file. The next
.B lch patch create
will produce a full state patch (TRUNCATE + INSERT for all tables).
.SH CONFIGURATION
Configuration is read from
.B config.toml
or
.B config.json
inside the
.B .leech2
work directory.
.SS Tables
Each table is defined under
.BR [tables.\fIname\fR] .
.TP
.BI source " = \(dqpath.csv\(dq"
Path to the CSV file, relative to the work directory or absolute.
.TP
.BI header " = true"
When true, the first CSV row is treated as a header and fields are matched by
name (columns may appear in any order; extra CSV columns are ignored). When
false (the default), columns are mapped to fields by position.
.PP
Each table must define one or more fields, each with a
.BR name ,
.BR type ,
and optionally
.BR primary\-key .
At least one field must have
.BR "primary\-key = true" .
Field names within a table must be unique.
.PP
Supported field types:
.TP
.B TEXT
Quoted as a single-quoted SQL string literal with escaping.
.TP
.B NUMBER
Emitted as a bare numeric literal. Validated as a finite
.BR f64 .
.TP
.B BOOLEAN
Emitted as
.B TRUE
or
.BR FALSE .
Accepts
.BR true / false ,
.BR 1 / 0 ,
.BR t / f ,
.BR yes / no .
.PP
These types control SQL quoting only. Your target database may use any
compatible column type (e.g.
.BR INTEGER ,
.BR FLOAT ,
.BR TIMESTAMP ).
.PP
Fields can have an optional
.B null
sentinel that specifies which CSV value should be emitted as SQL
.B NULL
instead of a typed literal. This is not allowed on primary-key fields.
.SS Injected fields
Optional
.B [[injected\-fields]]
entries add static columns to all generated SQL. Each entry becomes an extra
column in INSERT statements and an extra condition in DELETE/UPDATE WHERE
clauses. When any injected fields are configured, state-payload patches use
.B "DELETE FROM ... WHERE ..."
instead of
.B TRUNCATE
so that other agents' data is preserved.
.PP
Each entry requires
.BR name ,
.BR type ,
and
.BR value .
The
.B type
field accepts the same values as table field types.
.PP
Fields can also be injected at runtime with
.BR "lch patch inject" ;
runtime values overwrite any statically declared field with the same name.
.SS Filters
An optional
.B [filters]
section drops records at CSV load time. Filtered records never enter state,
deltas, or SQL output.
.TP
.BI max\-field\-length " = N"
Drop records where any field value exceeds
.I N
characters.
.PP
.B [[filters.exclude]]
entries define exclusion rules.
Each rule specifies a
.B field
name and one or both of:
.TP
.BI equals " = \(dqvalue\(dq"
Drop records where the field exactly matches the value.
.TP
.BI contains " = \(dqvalue\(dq"
Drop records where the field contains the value as a substring.
.PP
When both are set, either matching is sufficient to drop the record. An optional
.B tables
list restricts the rule to specific tables; when omitted, the rule applies to
all tables. If the named field does not exist in a table, the rule is silently
skipped.
.PP
Filtering happens before state computation. When a previously-included record
starts matching a filter, it appears as a DELETE in the next delta. When a
previously-filtered record stops matching, it appears as an INSERT.
.SS Compression
An optional
.B [compression]
section controls patch compression. Patches are compressed with zstd by default.
.TP
.BI enable " = true"
Enable or disable zstd compression (default: true).
.TP
.BI level " = 3"
Compression level (defaults to zstd default).
.SS History truncation
An optional
.B [truncate]
section controls automatic pruning of old block files after every
.BR "lch block create" .
All fields are optional and independent.
.TP
.BI max\-blocks " = N"
Keep at most
.I N
blocks in the chain (must be >= 1).
.TP
.BI max\-age " = \(dq7d\(dq"
Remove blocks older than the given duration. Supported suffixes:
.B s
(seconds),
.B m
(minutes),
.B h
(hours),
.B d
(days),
.B w
(weeks).
.TP
.BI remove\-orphans " = true"
Remove blocks on disk that are not reachable from HEAD (default: true).
.TP
.BI truncate\-reported " = true"
Remove blocks older than the last reported position (default: true).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B LEECH2_LOG
Controls the log level for messages written to stderr. Accepted values:
.BR error ,
.BR warn ,
.BR info ,
.BR debug ,
.BR trace .
Trace messages are only emitted in debug builds.
.TP
.B PAGER
Program used to paginate output when it exceeds the terminal height and stdout
is a terminal. Defaults too
.B less
on Unix and
.B more
on Windows.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B .leech2/
Work directory created by
.BR "lch init" .
Contains all configuration, state, and block files.
.TP
.B .leech2/config.toml
Table definitions, field schemas, filters, compression settings, and history
truncation configuration. May also be
.BR config.json .
.TP
.B .leech2/HEAD
Current block hash (the tip of the chain).
.TP
.B .leech2/REPORTED
Hash of the last successfully applied patch. Used as the default starting point
for
.BR "lch patch create" .
Removed by
.BR "lch patch failed" .
.TP
.B .leech2/STATE
Protobuf-encoded snapshot of all table states.
.TP
.B .leech2/PATCH
Last generated patch, written by
.BR "lch patch create" .
.TP
.BI .leech2/ hash
Block files, named by their SHA-1 content hash.
.SH CONCURRENCY
See
.BR libleech2 (3)
for details on safe concurrent use of a work directory and on the atomic-write
contract expected of CSV source files.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred. The error message is printed to stderr.
.SH EXAMPLES
Initialize a work directory and create the first block:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ lch init
Initialized .leech2

$ lch block create
a1b2c3d4e5f6...
.fi
.RE
.PP
Edit the CSV, create another block, and generate SQL:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ vim .leech2/products.csv
$ lch block create
f7e8d9c0b1a2...

$ lch patch create
$ lch patch sql
BEGIN;
INSERT INTO products (id, name, price) VALUES (4, 'Headphones', 59.99);
COMMIT;

$ lch patch applied
f7e8d9c0b1a2...
.fi
.RE
.PP
If SQL application fails, reset to force a full state on the next patch:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ lch patch failed
REPORTED removed; next patch will be a full state
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR libleech2 (3)
.PP
Full documentation and source code:
.UR https://github.com/larsewi/leech2
.UE
